<h2 class="govuk-heading-l" id="data">
  The data we use and how we use it
</h2>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Behaviour entries
</h3>
<p>
  Entries related to behaviour are extracted from the casenotes entered into NOMIS by selecting only casenotes with the type Positive or Negative.
  Subtypes are not considered.
</p>
<p>
  Only casenotes that are marked as POS or NEG from the case_note_type column within nomis_sens.offender_case_notes are included within the definition of Positive or Negative casenotes.
</p>
<p>
  It is worth noting that the date the casenote was entered into NOMIS may differ from when the incident in the casenote happened.
</p>
<p>
  Behaviour entries are associated with a prisoner’s wing at the time of recording in NOMIS.
  This might not always reflect the wing they were in at the time the casenote happened.
</p>
<p>
  A prisoner’s location is not contained within the casenotes table and therefore any analysis by wing is extracted from the prison population.
</p>
<p>
  <a href="#appendix-behaviour-entries">
    See appendix for category table
  </a>
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Incentive levels
</h3>
<p>
  Entry level has been removed from all analysis.
  Due to data quality issues on NOMIS there are a handful of prisoners on Entry incorrectly still in the prison population.
</p>
<p>
  Additional incentive levels above enhanced can be added by Governors.
  These new incentive levels will automatically be captured and displayed as ‘New incentive’ on the charts.
</p>
<p>
  <a href="#appendix-incentive-levels">
    See appendix for category table
  </a>
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">
  Protected characteristics
</h3>
<p>
  Sexual orientation and disability data have a lot of missing entries, with approximately 12 percent of missing data for sexual orientation and 40 percent for disability.
  We code all missing data for these two characteristics as ‘Unknown’.
</p>
<p>
  For sexual orientation, there are ‘Undisclosed’ records.
  Because we don’t know if this is recorded based on the actual meaning - that is, refused to say and not asked respectively – these are grouped as ‘Unknown’.
</p>
<p>
  The ethnicity Chinese is recorded under two categories in NOMIS – A4 Asian/Asian British: Chinese and O1 Chinese.
  In the data presented in this digital service, these 2 categories are grouped into Asian or Asian British.
</p>
<p>
